{"cursor":"8499","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nA 'continental divide' is a drainage divide on a continent such that the\ndrainage basin on one side of the divide feeds into one cean]] or sea, and the\nbasin on the other side either feeds into a different ocean or sea, or else is\nendorheic, not connected to the open sea.\n\nThe endpoints where a continental divide meets the coast are not always\ndefinite, because the exact border between adjacent bodies of water is usually\nnot clearly defined. The International Hydrographic Organization's publication\nLimits of Oceans and Seas defines exact boundaries of oceans, but it is not\nuniversally recognized. Where a continental divide meets an endorheic basin,\nsuch as the Great Divide Basin of Wyoming, the continental divide splits and\nencircles the basin.\n","linknr":250,"url":"Continental_divide","recorded":1362584100,"links":23,"instances":["river"],"pdf":["https://www.dmr.nd.gov/ndgs/NEWSLETTER/NLS03/pdf/Divide.pdf","https://www.dmr.nd.gov/ndgs/NEWSLETTER/NLS03/pdf/Divide.pdf","http://www.state.nd.us/ndgs/Newsletter/NLS03/pdf/Divide.pdf"],"categories":["Water divides","Montane ecology"],"headings":["Examples","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/NorthAmerica-WaterDivides.png/250px-NorthAmerica-WaterDivides.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b1/Ocean_drainage.png/250px-Ocean_drainage.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Canada_flag_map.svg/32px-Canada_flag_map.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a4/Flag_of_the_United_States.svg/32px-Flag_of_the_United_States.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Flag_of_Mexico.svg/32px-Flag_of_Mexico.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/ima